        <br><br>
        <p>This metal art form was born in Haiti in the early 1950's by the blacksmith, Georges Liautaud. It was at the encouragement of an American teacher, DeWitt Peters, who in 1944 opened the Le Centre d'Art in Port-au-Prince that Georges Liautaud expanded into the creation of decorative metal sculptures. </p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid__item large--one-third text-center">
        <h2>The Craft</h2>
        <img src="{{ 'Croix-Des-Bouquets-Craft-1.jpg' | asset_url }}">
        <br><br>
        <p>Recycled 55-gallon oil drums are carefully and skillfully transformed into a flattened ``metal canvas;`` then with chalk, the design is drawn onto the metal sheet. Using hammer, chisel and various primitive tools, the shape is cut and the various decorative patterns are pounded into the metal, creating a unique and treasured piece of primitive art.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid__item large--one-third text-center">
        <h2>The Impact</h2>
        <img src="{{ 'Croix-Des-Bouquets-Impact-1.jpg' | asset_url }}">
        <br><br>
        <p>In the devastating earthquake of 2010, Croix-des-Bouquets opened its city to 10,000 refugees from Port-au-Prince. Hope was restored as Paul Farmer's 'Partners in Health' relocated many victims. The metal artisans continue to support city's economy by using its model of up cycling, undertaking waste management while creating beautiful works of art from scrap metal.</p>
      </div>
